Europe
[1] France
Date: Mon 12 Sep 2011
Source: Destinationsante,com [in French, trans. & edited]
http://www.destinationsante.com/Rougeole-deja-6-morts-en-2011-en-France.html


The measles epidemic continues to escalate in France. The Institute
for Public Health and the National Academy of Medicine are alarmed and
calling for an enhanced immunisation programme. According to
academician Prof. Pierre Begue, "Since 2008, more than 20 000 cases
have been recorded by the Institute for Public Health, with 14 500 of
these reports being reported during the period January to June 2011
compared with 5000 (2 deaths) during the whole of 2010."

The regions most affected by the epidemic wave are located in the
South of France. "This outbreak of measles is particularly serious
because it affects predominantly infants under one year and adults,"
said Prof. Pierre Begue. Indeed, in 2010, incidence rates have more
than tripled in infants and have increased 5-fold in those over 20
years of age when compared with 2009 data. "Hospitalizations reached
nearly 40 percent in the case of infants infected with measles and 50
percent for those over 30 years. Complications were observed in 26
percent of 20-29 year-olds and 41 percent in the case of over 30
year-olds." The complications included pneumonia, neurological
complications and acute encephalitis. During the 1st 7 months of 2011,
15 cases had a neurological complication, 639 had severe pneumonia,
and 6 died, according to the Institute for Public Health as of 9 Sep
2011.

The measles epidemic has raged throughout Europe since 2006, with 12
036 cases reported in 2006-2007, half of them in Britain and
Switzerland. But according to the WHO Office for Europe, France is now
experiencing the largest epidemic and is contaminating neighboring
countries. "This is due to the fact that vaccination coverage requires
at least 95 percent coverage of the population. This is a consequence
of the extreme infectiousness of measles virus, which defines the rate
of reproduction, which is 15 to 20 times higher than that of
influenza." However in 2006, vaccination coverage in France was 90
percent for the 1st dose. However in the case of the 2nd dose, the
figure was only 44 percent at 6 years of age, when it should have been
80 percent.

Pierre Begue stressed that to contain the outbreak, it will be
necessary to enhance infant vaccination coverage and strictly enforce
measures for catch-up vaccination of children, adolescents and young
adults up to age 31. A more sustained public information campaign
would be desirable.

--
