The Americas
[5] Colombia (Atlantica)
Date: Tue 13 Sep 2011
Source: El Tiempo.com [machine trans. edited]
http://www.eltiempo.com/vida-de-hoy/salud/brote-de-sarampion-en-la-costa-atlantica_10349085-4


With the mass vaccination of 209 000 adolescents and young people
between 10 and 19 years in the Atlantic Coast [Atlantica], health
authorities are seeking to contain the outbreak of measles that so far
has claimed 5 confirmed cases in Barranquilla. That 10-19 age group
would be the most vulnerable sector of the population because,
according to experts, these ages have low vaccination coverage for
this disease.

All children under 8 years, however, would be immunized in subsequent
campaigns to eradicate rubella and measles. As of November 2010, 6 854
805 children of 1-8 years throughout the country have been immunized.

Like the flu, the disease caused by measles virus has symptoms that
include high fever, cough, redness and peeling of the skin. It can be
acquired through contact with droplets expelled into the air when an
infected person sneezes or coughs.

According to the health authorities, the 1st case was imported from
Brazil, a 14-year-old who had visited Sao Paulo, between 21 and 25 Jul
2011. Shortly after the index case developed symptoms of measles, his
5-year-old brother fell ill, followed by the mother of 2 teenagers and
2 close family members.

The Institute's director recalled that the last outbreak of measles
occurred in 2002, with 6000 suspected cases. "At that time, 139 cases
were confirmed, a situation that generated a multi-faceted
epidemiological response and a vaccination campaign that managed to
contain this outbreak," said Lopez.

