[8] USA (Wisconsin)
Date: Mon 12 Sep 2011
Source: The Journal Sentinel, Milwaukee [abbreviated & edited]
<http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/news/129686988.html


As part of the ongoing investigation into a confirmed case of measles,
the Milwaukee Health Department is asking anyone who visited a south
side building on 2 Sep 2011 to speak with a public health nurse
because they may have been exposed to the highly contagious disease.
To date, there are no new confirmed cases beyond the single case in a
child confirmed last week, Milwaukee Health Department Spokeswoman
Raquel Filmanowicz said Monday [12 Sep 2011]. But public health
officials have not been able to contact everyone who might have come
into contact with the child.

The child visited the Social Security Administration office at 1710 S.
7th St. between 9 a.m. and 1 p.m. on Sat 2 Sep 2011 and was contagious
at the time. The child is a refugee whose family moved to the city at
the end of August 2011. Because measles is highly contagious and can
be spread through coughing or sneezing while passing in a hallway,
officials also want to reach anyone who was at the Planned Parenthood
of Wisconsin offices in the same building at that time. Those who
visited either office between 9 a.m. and 1 p.m. on 2 Sep 2011 are
asked to call the Milwaukee Health Department at (414) 286-3521
between 8 a.m. and 4:30 p.m., Monday through Friday, to speak with a
public health nurse.

Parents across the city also should be sure their children are
up-to-date with required immunizations in the coming weeks, Health
Department officials said Monday [12 Sep 2011]. Adults born on or
after 1957 who do not know their measles vaccination status should
consider getting vaccinated against measles at this time, since the
disease can cause serious complications, including death.

Vaccination provides 99 percent protection against measles. Anyone
with symptoms of fever and rash should seek care and a diagnosis from
a medical provider and self-isolate until symptoms resolve. People
with measles symptoms should call their health care provider before
going to a clinic to receive instructions to prevent possible spread
of the disease.

Questions may be directed to the local public health department
regarding measles vaccination, symptoms or disease. In Milwaukee,
residents can call (414) 286-3521 between 8 a.m. and 4:30 p.m., Monday
through Friday, or visit the website,
http://www.milwaukee.gov/health. Vaccination clinics will be held
this week at all Health Department satellite health centers.

[Byline: Karen Herzog]

--
